"# Chapter 2 — Vectors and the dot product

A vector is a list of numbers with directions attached. That is not a
metaphor. In two dimensions the vector `[3, 4]` is an arrow that goes
right three and up four. In three dimensions `[3, 4, 5]` goes right,
up, and toward you. In two hundred dimensions the vector is an arrow
in a space you cannot picture, and that is fine — the arithmetic still
works and the ideas still apply.

Language models live in high-dimensional vector space. A word is a
vector. A sentence position is a vector. The state of the model
mid-computation is a vector. To understand what a language model does
you have to be comfortable with vector arithmetic, and that starts
here.

## What Motoi gives you

Motoi ships `vec/` verbs that do the arithmetic. You will use them
constantly. The core five are:

- `(list 1 2 3))` — build a vector from a list.
- `(vec/add a b)` — component-wise addition.
- `(vec/scale v k)` — multiply every component by a scalar.
- `(vec/dot a b)` — the dot product (a scalar).
- `(vec/norm v)` — the length of the vector (a scalar).

If you can do those five, you can do most of chapter 12. That is not
a joke.

## Problem 1 — Build one, add one

```
(define a (list 1 2 3))
(define b (list 4 5 6))
(display (vec/add a b))
;; => a vector with components [5 7 9]
```

Notice that `vec/add` operates component-wise. The first of `a` pairs
with the first of `b`, the second with the second, and so on. If the
vectors have different lengths the operation fails. That is a
design choice: ML code errors that would otherwise become silent bugs
are caught at the shape check.

## Problem 2 — Scale a vector

```
(define v (list 1 2 3))
(display (vec/scale v 2))
;; => [2 4 6]
```

Every component multiplied by 2. This is the operation that lets you
control the strength of a signal. In chapter 6 we will scale gradients
by a learning rate. Same verb, same idea.

## Problem 3 — The dot product

This is the operation of the book. Read it slowly.

The dot product of two vectors `a` and `b` of the same length is:

```
a·b = a[0]*b[0] + a[1]*b[1] + a[2]*b[2] + ... + a[n-1]*b[n-1]
```

You pair up the components, multiply each pair, and sum the products.
The result is one number.

```
(define a (list 1 2 3))
(define b (list 4 5 6))
(display (vec/dot a b))
;; => 32     (because 1*4 + 2*5 + 3*6 = 4 + 10 + 18 = 32)
```

Three things to know about the dot product.

**One.** It measures alignment. If `a` and `b` point the same
direction, the dot product is big and positive. If they point
perpendicular directions, it is zero. If they point opposite
directions, it is big and negative. This will be the mechanism the
attention head uses to decide which token to look at.

**Two.** It equals `|a| * |b| * cos(θ)` where `θ` is the angle
between them and `|a|` is the length. That is the geometric
interpretation. You do not need to memorize it. You do need to
believe it: dot product measures how much two vectors agree.

**Three.** `vec/dot a a` gives you the squared length of `a`. Try it.

```
(define v (list 3 4))
(display (vec/dot v v))
;; => 25       (because 3*3 + 4*4 = 9 + 16 = 25)
(display (vec/norm v))
;; => 5        (because sqrt(25) = 5)
```

The vector `[3, 4]` has length 5. Pythagoras from 500 BC, still the
same trick.

## Problem 4 — Cosine similarity

Two vectors are 'similar' if they point the same way. The angle
between them is small. Cosine of a small angle is close to 1. Cosine
of a right angle is 0. Cosine of a reverse angle is -1.

So the cosine of the angle between `a` and `b` measures similarity on
a scale from -1 (opposite) to 1 (same direction). And by the
geometric interpretation of dot product:

```
cos(θ) = (a·b) / (|a| * |b|)
```

Let's compute one.

```
(define (cosine-similarity a b)
  (/ (vec/dot a b)
     (* (vec/norm a) (vec/norm b))))

(define north (list 0 1))
(define northeast (list 1 1))
(define east (list 1 0))

(display (cosine-similarity north north))
;; => 1               (a vector is perfectly similar to itself)

(display (cosine-similarity north east))
;; => 0               (perpendicular directions, similarity 0)

(display (cosine-similarity north northeast))
;; => 0.7071067...    (cosine of 45 degrees)
```

Cosine similarity is how language models decide which words are near
each other in meaning. Two word-vectors that point similar directions
mean similar things. We will build the vocabulary space in chapter 11.

## Problem 5 (composed) — Nearest neighbor in a small vocabulary

Given a query vector and a small list of labeled vectors, find the
label whose vector is most similar to the query. This is a search
by vector alignment — the core of every embedding lookup.

```
(define (cosine-similarity a b)
  (/ (vec/dot a b)
     (* (vec/norm a) (vec/norm b))))

(define vocab
  (list
    (list 'cat  (list 0.9 0.1 0.2))
    (list 'dog  (list 0.8 0.2 0.3))
    (list 'car  (list 0.1 0.9 0.4))
    (list 'tree (list 0.2 0.1 0.9))))

(define query (list 0.85 0.15 0.25))

(define (score-entry entry)
  ;; entry looks like ('cat (0.9 0.1 0.2)). Value is (cadr entry).
  (list (car entry) (cosine-similarity query (cadr entry))))

(define scores (map score-entry vocab))

(define (best xs)
  (if (null? (cdr xs))
      (car xs)
      (let ((rest-best (best (cdr xs))))
        (if (> (cadr (car xs)) (cadr rest-best))
            (car xs)
            rest-best))))

(display (best scores))
;; => (cat 0.9998...)
```

The query is closer to `cat` than to any other word. Real word
embeddings do exactly this at scale: 50,000 vectors each 768
dimensions long, and a search that returns the closest match. Same
verbs, larger tensors.

## Capstone — Distance in high dimension

Build a random 128-dimensional vector and check that a scaled copy of
itself has cosine similarity 1.

```
(define (random-vec dim)
  (vec/make (map (lambda (_) (- (* (random) 2) 1))
                 (iota dim))))

(define v (random-vec 128))
(define scaled (vec/scale v 3.7))

(define sim
  (/ (vec/dot v scaled)
     (* (vec/norm v) (vec/norm scaled))))

(display sim)
;; => 1.0 (or 0.9999999... depending on floating-point rounding)
```

Cosine similarity does not care about scale. It cares about direction.
That is exactly the property we want for word meaning: 'cat' and
'CAT' should end up in the same corner of the space no matter how
loud someone said it.

## Why this matters

Every attention head in a transformer computes many dot products every
step. Every embedding lookup is a similarity search. Every gradient
update is a vector addition. This chapter is the operation the whole
rest of the book compounds. Get it in your fingers.

## What's next

In chapter 3 we move up one dimension. A matrix is a stack of
vectors. Matrix-vector multiplication is a stack of dot products.
Once you see that, you see the entire fully-connected layer.
")
